definition.value: A hydrate that is the hemipentahydrate form of cadmium dichloride.
A hydrate that is the dihydrate form of sodium tungstate. Combines with hydrogen peroxide for the oxidation of secondary amines to nitrones
An inorganic sodium salt having tungstate as the counterion. Combines with hydrogen peroxide for the oxidation of secondary amines to nitrones.
Any lactone in which the cyclic carboxylic ester group forms a part of a cyclic macromolecule.
A tripeptide in which three glycine units are linked via peptide bonds in a linear sequence.
An octadecatetraenedioic acid obtained by oxidative degradation of leukotriene B4, a process that results in the removal of C19 and C20 with concomitant dioxygenation of C18.
A C18 alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid having four double bonds at unspecified positions in the chain.
A monoacylglycerol phosphate having palmitoyl as the acyl group on O-1 and with the phosphate group on O-3.
A beta-D-glucan of more than 20 D-glucose residues joined by beta-(1->3) and beta-(1->6) glycosidic linkages.
Any substance which is added to food to preserve or enhance its flavour and/or appearance.

A tetrahydronicotinamide adenine dinucleotide obtained by formal stereo- and regioselective hydration across the 2,3-double bond in the nicotinyl ring of NADPH, with the hydroxy group located at position 2, having (S)-configuration.

A tetrahydronicotinamide adenine dinucleotide obtained by formal stero- and regioselective hydration across the 2,3-double bond in the nicotinyl ring of NADPH, with the hydroxy group located at position 2, having (R)-configuration.
An organic sodium salt resulting from the replacement of the proton from the carboxy group of butyric acid by a sodium ion.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is 4-hydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydrogen at position 3 is substituted by a decaprenyl group.

An oxalate salt obtained by reaction of 5-nonyloxytryptamine with one equivalent of oxalic acid. 5-HT1B selective agonist, several times more potent than sumatriptan and inactive as a 5-HT1A agonist (Ki at 5-HT1B = 1 nM, selectivity over 5-HT1A > 300-fold).
An organic salt derived from oxalic acid.

A 19-membered macrocyle that is geldanamycin in which the methoxy substituent attached to the benzoquinone moiety has been replaced by an allylamino group. It is a potent inhibitor of heat shock protein 90 (Hsp90). A less toxic analogue than geldanamycin, it induces apoptosis and displays antitumour effects.
A flavan-3,3',4,4',5,5',7-heptol that has (2R,3S,4S) configuration.
A deoxyheptose that is L-glycero-D-manno-heptopyranose in which the 7-hydroxy group is substituted by hydrogen.
Any C7 deoxy sugar having at least one hydroxy group replaced by hydrogen.
Inorganic nitrate salt of calcium.
An organic sodium salt that is the monosodium salt of glutamic acid.

An erythromycin that consists of erythronolide A having 2,6-dideoxy-3-C-methyl-alpha-L-ribo-hexopyranosyl and 3,4,6-trideoxy-3-(dimethylamino)-beta-D-xylo-hexopyranosyl residues attahced at positions 4 and 6 respectively.
An aromatic ether that is phenol substituted on oxygen by a 2-hydroxyethyl group.
The calcium salt of cyanamide, formed when calcium carbide reacts with nitrogen
A 7-deazaguanine ribonucleoside that is queuosine having a beta-D-mannosyl residue attached at position 5''.
Cytidine in which the 2-keto group on the cytosine ring is substituted by an epsilon-Llysyl residue.
Cytidine in which the 2-keto group on the cytosine ring is substituted by the amino group of agmatine.
A thiouridine that is 2-thiouridine bearing an additional carboxymethylaminomethyl substituent at position 5 on the thiouracil ring.
A derivative of uridine, bearing an additional carboxymethylaminomethyl substituent at position 5 on the uracil ring.
A glycosylglucose formed by a beta-(1->4)-linkage between D-mannose and D-glucose.
An organic amino compound in which an aminoalkyl group is linked to an arene.
A 1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl group is specified as oleyl (9Z-octadecenyl).
Meroterpenoids are complex organooxygen natural products produced from polyketide and terpenoid precursors.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 34 carbons in total with 4 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 34 carbons in total with 3 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl groups contain forty carbons in total with six double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 36 carbons in total and 2 double bonds.
A glycerophosphocholine that is an alkyl,acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl or acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 contain a total of 38 carbons and 5 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 38 carbons with 3 double bonds.
An organic aromatic compound whose structure contains two aromatic rings or ring systems, joined to each other by a single bond.
Lignin composed principally of trans-p-coumaryl alcohol units.
Lignin composed principally of coniferol (guaiacyl) units.
Lignin composed principally of trans-sinapyl alcohol (syringyl) units.
A glycerophosphocholine that is an alkyl,acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl or acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 contain a total of 38 carbons and 4 double bonds.

A lysophosphatidylcholine in which the acyl group contains 20 carbons with 3 double bonds. If R1 is an acyl group and R2 is a hydrogen then the molecule is a 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine. If R1 is a hydrogen and R2 is an acyl group then the molecule is a 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine.
A glycerophosphocholine that is glycero-3-phosphocholine bearing two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2.

A lysophosphatidylcholine in which the remaining acyl group is specified as tetradecanoyl (myristoyl). If R1 is the acyl group and R2 is a hydrogen then the molecule is a 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine.  If R1 is a hydrogen and R2 is the acyl group then the molecule is a 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine.
A sphingomyelin d18:1 in which the amino group of sphingosine is substituted by a pentadecanoyl group.
A sphingomyelin d18:1 in which the N-acyl group is specified as tetradecanoyl (myristoyl).
